         Drexyll,</P><P>You are right the US is a representative republic.  I used democracy in a generic form.  But, in essence, you shot down your own argument by making this semantic point.  We elect people to run the show for a period of time.  If we like the work they've done, we re-elect them.  If we don't, we elect someone else.  In this way, the government reports to the people.  If you don't like the way Bush handled the Clinton pardon scandal or the fact that we are in NAFTA, you can vote for someone else in 2004.  If enough people in enough states feel the same way you do, then he will lose.  In this way, he reports to the people.  The same goes for Congress.  </P><P>Direct democracy would not work in a country as large as the US.  The Founders knew this even back when the country was much smaller than it is today.</P><P>BTW, the only thing I find interesting in the survey link you provided is that this survey took place under Bill Clinton.  I don't take this survey, if in fact it really happened, to be any indication as to how the government views the people in general.  I have no doubt that Special Forces are asked a number of things, just to see how they might respond.</P><P><BR> <a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height="15" width="15" border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
